{"/service/ndnp/scu/batch_scu_kiwi_ver03/data/sn86063758/00517016585/1927031101/0363.xml":{"full_text":"VOLUME LXIII, NUMBER 20\nNEWBERRY, S. C.,\nFRIDAY, MARCH 11, 1927\nTWICE A WEEK, $1.50 A YEAR\nBUSINESS# OUTLOOK\nVERY PROMISWNG\nSO SAY NEWBERRY MER\nCHANTS AND BUSINESS MEN.\nInterviews With Merchants and\nBusiness Men Who Attended Ban\nquet Monday Evening.\nThe Herald and News thought it\nwould be a fine thing to find out\nwhat .some of the merchants- and\nbusiness men thought of the meet\ning and banquet given last Monday\nnight, and what effect, if any, it\nwould have on the business outlook\nof the town in the future, and would\nhave been glad to have had an ex\npression from all of those who were\npresent, but we just took them at\nrandom and tried not to overlook\nany one, and if some one has beefl\nmissed there was no intention to\npick. The spirit of optimism seem\ned to fill the atmosphere at the meet\ning, and the enthusiasm,, about\nwhich several of the speakers talked,\nas so necessary to the growth and\ndevelopment of any community, was\nso much in evidence that The Herald\nand News thought it might have a\ngood influence over some who were\nnot present to get those present to\nexpress in a- sentence or two just\nhow they were impressed by the\nmeeting, and what they thought of\nthe future. No town or community\ncan grow and:- prosper where the\npeople who make ,the town do not\nbelieve\u2019 in their town. They must\nhave confidence in themselves first,\nand then they must have confidence\nin their town, and they must believe\nin it. This is; good town, but un\nless the people who live in it have\nconfidence in it and believe in it,\nthere can be very little developmnt\nand growth. It will just dry up.\nMr. Duncan Johnson of Johnson\nMcCrackin company, said it was a\nfine meeting and the spirit of the\nmeeting means a better understand\ning among the merchants, and con\nsequently more cooperation for the\nthings that will hel pthe town grow.\nThe big power development on the\nSaluda river means, if it means\nanything, jthat this section, instead\nof a farming section, will change to\na manufacturing community, and,\nalso that the farms would have to\nchange from cotton to the raising\nof the things that the new popula\ntion would need, and give a market\nfor these things.\nMT. Frank Lominack of Lomi\nnack\u2019s Hardware, said the meeting\ncould not have been better, and the\nfine spirit that prevailed meant\ngreat things for the future of New\nberry, and all of us should be en\ncouraged by the coming into our\nvery midst of the great power plant\non the Saluda river, and Newberry\nwas just the right distance from the\ngreat lake that is to be and fortu\nnate in being above the dam.\nMr. M. L. Spearman, vice-presi\ndent of the Exchange Bank, said it\nwas a good and enthusiastic meet-\ning, and we all should have gotten\ninspiration from the fine spirit\nwhich prevailed. We should go for- j\nward with more determination to\ndo our part in cooperating in all j\ncommunity development. We should i\nfeel encouraged to go to work and i\npractice thrift, and devote our per-\nsonal energy and lend our influence j\nto helping all good proposals that j\nare for the betterment of our com-\nmunity, and the future looks bright j\nfor all industries, and if we will all\njust make up our minds to work to- j\ngether and stop any little bickering?\nthat we may indulge in, and blot\nout all jealousies and believe in\nNewberry, there will be good times\nahead. The great power develop\nment means a great deal for New-\nberry if we grasp the opportunity j\nthat is at our door knocking. j\nThe furniture firm of G. B. Sum- i\nmer and son gave the following1\nbrief and expressive statement: j\n\u2018'We can not help but feel the mer- j\nchants meeting held Monday night\nwas beneficial to all who attended, i\nThe Lexington power project, when j\ndeveloped, in our opinion, will be a\nbig asset for Newberry.\u201d 1\nMr. M. B. Hipp of the firm of\nCopeland-Hipp company is enthusi\nastic and gave The Herald and News\nthe following statement: \u201cIn re- j\n(Continued on page 7)\n<iN <i>\n<S>\nLITTLE LOCALS. 4>\nj\n$><\u00ae-<?><S\u00bb4!><$>$><8>\u00ab><a-<e><8><8><a><&<8><S>!\nMr. Ellis Boland, who lives in the 1\nMollohon mill village, is a chicken\nfancier, and he takes great pride in\nhis yard of fine Rhode Island Reds.\nHe showed The Herald and News an\negg the other day from one of his\nhens that weighed one fourth of a\npound, and one way was 8 1-2 inches\nin cirmumferenge, around, and 4 1-4\ninches the other way. It was cone\nshaped and seemed to have a couple\nyellows, or in other words to be a\ntwin egg.\nThere are lots of people in this\ncounty engaged in the chicken busi\nness, and when the great power de\nvelopment gets well under way the\nmarket for eggs and chickens and\nmany other things will be greatly\nincreased, and the farmers will then\nbe able to devote their energies to\nother crops than cotton, and will find\nthese crops profitable.\nI While the town force is fixing up\nI the sidewalk along Nance street, be\nI tween Friend and Boundary, how\nwould it do to pave the sidewalk and\nthen there would be no further need\nfor repairs, and in the end it would\nsave money, and be an investment\nthat would pay. This patch work in\nstreet and road work never pays.\nTime for the gardner to begin\nplanting. In fact, some of the gar\ndens around town are already look\ning well.\n0\nThe following jurors have been\ndrawn for the April term of federal\ncourt to be held at Greenville in\nApril 5: Petit jurors: J. II. Clary,\nNewberry; Will Webb, Chappells:\nJ. W. Gary, Whitmire; W. C.\nBrown, Jr., Newberry. For the\nterm beginning Monday, April 11:\nW. R. Reid, Sr., Newberry; G. E.\nYoung, Whitmire. For the term be\nginning April 18: J. B. Luther,\nProsperity; D. E. Schumpert, New\nI berry. For term beginning April\n25: J. Monroe Bickley, Newberry;\nAllen Murray, Newberry; J. W.\nMims, Newberry.\nMr. T. Roy Summer and A. A.\nCleland are attending federal court\nin Rock Hill as jurors.\nL. P. Gable from Anderson, who\nhas a chain of stores, has rented the\nvacant store room in the hotel block\nand Mi\u2019. Geo. W. Summer is having\nit fitted up to suit Mr. Gable. It if\nexpected that the store will be open\nfor business on Saturday, March\n19. He will handle gents\u2019 furnish\ning and ladies' ready-to-wear.\nIt is understood that the Fashion\nhas purchased the vacant lot in\nMain street, west of the Bryson\nGrocery store, and will erect a mod\nern and up-to-date department store\nroom for the large business of this\nestablishment. The store that is now\noccupied by the Fashion belongs\nto Mimnaugh and the lease expires\non the first of August when Mim\nnaugh will occupy his own store.\nThe merchants\u2019 meeting should\nhave inspired some of the merchants i\nof Newberry to start a regular and\nsystematic advertising campaign of\ntheir own stores, instead of just oc-\neasional advertising, to put on sped-\nal sales. It is the constant adver-\ntising that pays, keeping everlasting j\nat it is what brings success. And it\nwould not co-t any more to keep an\nadvertisement in the newspapers\nregularly than to spurt. It would\nhelp to stabilize the newspaper busi-\nness and then the publishers could\ngo along and work and help build\nand boost.\n_ i\n\nAs a result of the merchants1 ban- j\nquet held last Monday night, the\nboosters, committee of the chamber j\nof commerce met Wednesday after- j\nnoon and mapped out a program for j\nthe me-'ting called for Friday night, J\nMarch 1 1 at X o\u2019clock. The boosters\nare taking advantage of thi.- oppor\ntunity to boost Newberry and New\nberry\u2019s possibilities.\nENJOYABLE AFFAIR MONDAY\nEVENING.\nMany Guests From Neighboring\nTowns\u2014Mr. K\u2019.\u2018.ester of Charlotte\nPrincipal Speaker.\nThat was a fine meeting' of the\nmerchants and business men of\nNewberry around the banquet table\nat the Newberry hotel on Monday\nevening. There were a number of\nprominent guests from our neighbor\ning towns, and they all scented to\nimbibe the spirit which prevailed\nduring the entire evening.\nDr. Derrick believes in psychol\nogy, and he thinks the pscychologi\ncal moment has arrived in Newber\nry at this time, and it is now for the\npeople of this community to awake\nand take advantage of the opportuni\nty. He sees in the development of\nthe great water power down on the\nSaluda river a great thing for the\nsection in which it is located, and,\nnot only so, but for the entire south\nland. And it is especially an oppor\ntunity for Newberry and all this\nsection.\nIt is a big thing, and it is fortu\nnate for Newberry, even before the\ndevelopment begins, because the\npscychologieal effect will help all\nbusiness and give the business rc,<:n\nof the section courage and hope,\nand they can look to the future and\nsee that it holds something that is\u2019\ngood, if we only do our part, and\nthere is where the pscychology com.es\nin, it gives and arouses hope and\nstimulates and helps us to see that\nthe clouds are not so dark and low\nering as some may have felt that\nthey were. They have been lifted\nand the rift may he seen. It will\nhelp all of us to play the role of a\nPollyanna, and that is worth a whole\nlot, and sometimes more than mon\ney, because it gives something that\nmoney can not buy.\nMr. Kuester of North Carolina,\nwho was the principal speaker of the\nevening, did not arrive until late as\nthere had been heavy rains in and\naround Charlotte all of Monday af\nternoon, and he left that city in a\nheavy rain, hut he believed in keep\ning your appointment, and he ar\nrived by nine o\u2019clock, and he had two\nNorth Carolina merchants with him,\nand they all had a message which\nthey delivered. Mr. Kuester is a\nlive wire, and he told the merchants\nand others who were present, some\nwholesome truths which it is hoped\nwill soak in and hear fruit. He told\nthem, they must have faith in then\ntown and in themselves, and that\nthey must let other people hear of\nthe fait hwhich they had if they ex\npected any one to believe in them.\nThey must have ambition in them\nselves and for their town, and they\nmust let others know of their am\nbition. He told the merchants that\nif tey wanted their town and their\nlousiness to grow, they must adver\ntise in their local papers. The town\nwas judged by the character of the\nnewspaper it sustained, and no town\ncould grow and live without a live\nnewspaper, and no newspaper could\nlive that did not have the hearty\nsupport of the rnrechants, and that\nvery few of the small town news\npapers ever made any money, and\nyet they made the towns, for with\nout them there could be no worth\nwhile town. And Mr. Kuester told a\ngreat truth. Mr. Kuester also told\nthe merchants and business men\nthat a live chamber of commerce\nwas necessary to the live town, and\nthey should support J. P. Moon and\nthe chamber of commerce. He made\na good and a rousing talk, and it is\nhoped that his talk will result in\nmuch good.\nMr. Williams, who came with Mr.\nKuester, also made a fine talk, and\ntold the merchants what thej must\ndo, and he affirmed what Mr. Kuest\ner said about the support of the lo\ncal newspapers.\n:We are not going to undertake to\ngive a detailed report of the meet\ning, or of the speeches. The first to\nspeak was Mayor Wright, who was 1\nintroduced by the* presiding ollicer\nas tno keynote speaker. Mayor\nWright made a good talk, and then\n(Continued on page 5)\nI\nCal! For Citizens Meeting New\nj Court House, Friday Night, i\nMarch 11th, 8 O\u2019clock.\nI\nThe town and county of New- j;\nberry is facing immediately the j!\ngreatest industrial development j\nin its history\u2014on account of the\nassured development of the Sa-\nIuda Power company, right at\nour doe This development will\nbe larger than at Muscle Shoals\nand. its potential*possibilities to us\nare greater than we can con- j\nceive.\nThis call is for a! lof the\nbusiness men and women of our S\ncity and county who are really in-\nforested in the growth and de\nvelopment of our industrial and\nfanning interests to meet and\nplan in a most intelligent way to\nfurther our interest in this mat\nter. Hope the court house will\nbe filled to overflowing.\nBoosters Committee Newberry\nChamber of Commerce.\nBOOSTER MEETING\nFRIDAY EVENING\nEVERYBODY EXPECTED TO BE\nPRESENT AT COURT HOUSE\n_J_\nObject To Let Officers of Power\nDevelopment Know That New\nberry Ready To Cooperate.\nThere is to be a meeting of all the\ncitizens of Newberry, whether they\nbelong to the chamber of commerce\nor not, at the court house on Friday\nevening at 8 o\u2019clock, and every one\nwho is interested in the growth and\ndevelopment of Newberry, and who\nhas the vision to see just a little in\nthe future, while the light is burn\ning bright, is asked to come, and if\nyou are still blind-folded, come any\nway, because may be this meeting\nwill be able to take the hood from\nyour eyes. i\nThe idea is to strike while the iron\nis hot, and that is the only way the\ngood blacksmith can work and weld\nthe iron, to strike while it is hot. j\nThe purpose is to talk about New- I\nberry, and to boost just a little, and\nto appoint a committee to go to Co\nlumbia and to let the people of that\ntown and the officers of the power\ndevelopment, know that we are\nready in Newberry to cooperate with\nthem in all that they are doing for\nthe development of this fair section\nof South Carolina, and, in fact, of\nthe entire southland.\nTo let them know that we appre\nciate what is being done, and realize\nin part at least, its vastness, and\nwhat transformation it will make in\nthe life of this entire section. That\nwe hail it with delight, and want to\ndo what we can to speed the day\nwhen the great fresh water lake will\nhold the energy that will transform j\nthis section into the greatest manu\nfacturing community of the world,\nand that will invite, by its climate\nand other natural advantages, set-\ntiers from all sections of the world\nwho are seeking climate and beauty\nof nature and health.\nLet every citizen of the town\ncome out to the meeting on Friday\nevening and rejoice with us, all to- 1\ngether for your town.\nSPECIAL SERVICE AT\nSUMMER MEMORIAL\nOn next Sunday night, March 13, j\nat 7:45 there will be a special ser-\nvice under the auspice? of the Wo-\nman\u2019s Missionary Society of Summer j\nMemorial E. L. church, nothing pro-\nventing. The Rev. J. L. Cromer of j\nProsperity will preach the sermon.\nThe time has been changed from\n7:15 to 7:45 o\u2019clock, so as to ac\ncommodate the speaker for the even-j\ning. The public is cordially invited\nto this service.\nPlay at Rutherford j\nThe play that was given at Mt. j\nBethel-Carmany March 4. will ap-!\npear at Rutherford school house on\nFriday, March 11. Admission 15\nand 25 cents It is a good play anil\nif you have not seen it you will en\njoy it, and even if you have seen it\nyou can appreciate a repetition.\nDR, HALLMAN DIES\nAT SPARTANBURG\nVETERAN LUTHERAN MINISTER\nAND WORKER.\nWas Resident of Newberry For\nMany Years\u2014Fune.'al Held\nWednesday.\nSpartanburg, Mnwb S.\u2014Dr. S.\nT. Hallman, S3, trusieo of Newberry\ncollege, former president of the\nSouth Carolina Lutheran Synod, edi\ntor of many church publications,\nchurch histories and pastor ox the\nWoman\u2019s Memorial Evangelical\nLutheran church here for the past\n2o years, died at his home here this\nmorning.\nFuneral services will he held Wed\nnesday afternoon at 4 o\u2019clock. The\nbody will be taken from his late\nhome to the Lutheran church at 1\no\u2019clock where it v. ill lie in state\nuntil 4 o'clock when the funeral ser\nvices will be conducted by the Rev.\nH. J. Black of Columbia, president of\nthe South Carolina Synod of the\nUnited Lutheran Church in America.\nThe interment will be in Oakwood\ncemetery.\nHe is survived by his widow, three\nsons and live daughters as follows:\nProfessor E. B. Hallman, S. S. Hall\nman and Charles Hallman of Spar\ntanburg; Mrs. J. G. Carrier of Hick\nory, X. C., Mrs. Carl Littlejohn, Mrs.\nJ. E. Lawhon and Misses Ruth and\nKate Hallman of Spartanburg.\nDoctor Hallman was born in Lex\nington county, September 3, 1844.\nNeHvberry college furnished him his\nclassical training and he was grad\nuated from the Southern Lutheran\nTheological seminary in Cmumma\nin 1868 and received the degree *of\nM. A. and D. D. from- the Newberry\ninstitution. The same year on Oc\ntober 19 he was inducted into the\nministry by the South Carolina\nSynod of the Lutheran church and\nduring his long ministerial career\nhas served many churches in differ\nent sections of the South. While\nmost of his church activities have\nbeen centered in his native state he\nhas served congregations in North\nCarolina and Georgia.\nThe churches he has served during\nhis prolonged ministry are as fol\nlows\nCorinth and Good Hope, Saluda,\nNT. C., 1868-69; Pine Grove and Thin\nity churches, Orangeburg county,\n1869-75; St. Matthew's and Mt. Le\nbanon churches, Orangeburg coun\nty, 1875-80. Sa. James, Coldwater\nand Mt. Hermon churches, Concord,\nX.K\u2019., 1880-83. Methleheni, St. Phil\nip s anc! St. John's, Peruana, 1883\n88; Holy Trinity, Augusta, Ga.,\n1888-95; Grace and Mt. Tabor, Pros\nperity, 1895-1900. hollowing these\nhe supplied St. Philip\u2019s, Mt. Olivet\nand the Church of the Redeemer at\nNewberry tor a short time and No\nvember 8, 1900, was elected Pied\nmont missionary. It was through\nhis efforts that Immanuel church was\norganized at Greenwood September\n21, 1902, and tire Woman\u2019s Memori\nal church in this city, September 28,\n1902. For a time lie served the two\nchurches, jointly but the greater part\nof his ministry for the past quarter\nof a century has been devoted to\nthe pastorate of the Spartanburg\nLutheran church.\nChurch of the Redeemer.\n10:;]') a. m., Sunday school.\n11:30 a. in., morning; service. Sec\nond Sunday in Lent. -Sermon by\nKi'v. Louis G. Gray, missionary to\nJapan; subject: -The Heaiiny\nChrist.\u201d\n0:40 Senior and Interme\ndiato Luther League meetings.\nri :30 p. m., evonlmr service. This\nwill bo the closing survive of the\nweek of prayer. obsei ed by the Wo\nman s Missionary Society. The ser\nmon will bo preached by tlu* pastor:\nsubject, \"Lord, What Wilt Thou\nHave Me to Do?\u2019\u2019\nSpecial music will be provided for\ntaese services. A cordial invitation\nis extended to friends and visitors.\n\nScotsmen are accounting- for the\nlarge number of golf balls lost on\none o! the cour-cs at Bar-vick-on\nTweed. by assert inn that they are\neaten by cattle grazing on tiie\nlinks.\nDESECRATING THE STATE\u2019S\nSEAT OF GOVERNMENT\nState Capitol Becomes Place For\nPouring Out of Moonshine\nLiquor.\nSpecial to The Herald and News.\nI Columbia, March 10.\u2014The State\nHouse reeked with the odor of moon\nshine whiskey Wednesday night.\nDuring the afternoon, 180 gallons\nof whiskey, seized in Hell Hole\nswamp in Berkeley county and held\nfor 30 days in the death house of the\ni state penitentiary, were poured\nfrom their containers on the plaza\nat the foot of the State House steps,\nrunning into a sewer as a crowd of\ninterested\u2014-and perhaps thirsty\u2014\nspectators looked on. The sewer\nruns under the State House and\nduring the afternoon and night the\nfumes from the liquor filled the\nbuilding.\nEP WORTH LEAGUE PROGRAM\nFOR SUNDAY EVENING\nEpworth League program, March\n13. Time: 6:45 p. m. Subject:\nCommentations. Pianist: Miss Mar\ngaret Farrow,' violinist, Mr. C. L.\nHayes.\nI \u201cAbide With Me\u201d\u2014League.\nScripture, Psalm, 149-150\u2014Cald\nwell Sims.\nViolin Solo: \u201cHumoresque\u201d\u2014Mr.\nC. L, Kayes.\nPrayer\u2014Rqv. R. L. Plolroyd.\n\u201cWhen I Survey the Wonderous\nCross\u201d\u2014League.\nLeader\u2019s Topic: \u201cThe Epworth\nLeague Symbol.\u201d Introduction,\nCaldwell Sims. \u201cThe Sign\u201d, Otis\nWhitaker. \u201cEmploying Youth\u201d,\nEdward Schumpert.\nDuet: \u201cThe Invisible Land\u201d\u2014\nMisses Carabel West and Elizabeth\nSalter, with violin accompaniment.\nI \u201cChurch Hymnal Is Second to\nOnly One Other Book, the Bible\u201d\u2014\ni Miss Margaret Farrow.\n\u201cThe Influence of Other Hymns\u201d\n\u2014Miss Lucy Metts.\nI \u201cRock of Ages\u201d\u2014League.\nI Business.\nI Lord\u2019s prayer with benediction,\nj The public is cordially invited to\nattend the consecration service of\nthe union, Friday night, March 11,\nat 8 o\u2019clock, at Central. All leaguers\nare urged to come,\ni _-\nA. LOGAN WY3E\nDIES IN COLUMBIA\nj The State, 9th.\nj A. Logan Wyse, 86, Confederate\n1 veteran of Saluda county, died at\nj 8:15 yestreday morning at the Con\nfederate home after a short illness,\nj Wyse served with distinction\nI in the Confederate war as a member\nj of Kershaw\u2019s brigade, Company M,\nj Seventh regiment, South Carolina\nj volunteers. He entered the Confed\nI crate home in May, 1925, where he\nwas greatly beloved for his many\nfine qualities. He was a member of\nSaluda lodge, No. 103, A. F. M., and\ni \u00a3l devoted member of Corinth Lu\nI theran church, Saluda county.\nHe is survived by one brother, A. j\nj Wyse, of 1029 Elmwood avenue, i\nColumbia; by three sons, J. C.\nWyse and B. D. Wyse, both of Sa-!\nj luda, and B. B. Wyse of Jackson- j\nville, Fla.; also by two daughters, I\nMjss Adel la Wyse and Mrs. R. W.\nBass, both of Columbia.\nFuneral services will he held at j\nnoon today at Corinth Lutheran I\nchurch, Saluda county, with Masonic\nhonors.\nRevival Meeting.\nThe revival meeting will begin in\nRuling Memorial church Sunday,\nMai eh lotli, and continue possiblv\ntwo weens. Services each evenin'*1 at\n7:10 o\u2019clock.\nRev. R. I.. Holroyd, pastor of Cen\ntral Methodist church, will do the\npreaching for the meeting.\nBrother Holroyd is a young man\nof fine personality and good speech.\nYou will enjoy hearing him.\nThe public is cordially invited to\nall the services.\nB. H. Harvey, Pastor.\nAn individual electric power plant\nconsisting of a small generator,\nspring-driven, supplies sufiieient cur\nrent to operate a light bulb. Ten\nseconds of cranking by hand produc\nes three minutes of light.\nGENERAL ASSEMBLY\nMERELY CRAWLING\nSEEMS TO BE WITHOUT DEFI\nNITE PROGRAM.\nShealy and Pearman Defeated For\nReflection On Railroad Board.\nOther Matters.\nSpecial to The Herald and News.\nColumbia, March 10.\u2014Frank W.\nShealy of Lexington county, for 12\nyears a member of the state rail\nroad commission and for many years\nj its chairman, met with defeat in his\ni race for reelection Wednesday when\nT. H. Tatum of Bishopville won out.\nP. A. Hodges of Columbia was the\ni third candidate in this race. This\ni defeat of Mr. Shealy was the out\nstanding feature of the railroad\ncommission elections. In the seventh\nj district, three ballots had to be\ntaken before Tatum was named.\nIn the fifth district race, D. A.\nI Sapp of Lancaster was elected a\nmember of the railroad commission\nto succeed Gov. John G. Richards.\nI Mr. Sapp is father of Claude N. Sapp\nof Columbia, former chairman of\nthe ways and means committee in\nj the house. Mr. Sapp defeated Sen\nator James E. Beamguard of York\nin the race.\nJohn C. Coney of Reevesville was\nreelected a member of the commis\nsion, defeating J. D. Bowen of Sum\nj merton for the place from the first\ndistrict.\nj R. Homer McAdams of Due West\nwas victor in the third congression\nal district race, winning out over\nJames N. Pearman of Anderson.\nJ. H. Nance of Cross Hill was re\nI elected a member of the commission\ni from the fourth district, defeating\nWalter S. Wingo, representative\nj from. Spartanburg and- Henry H.\nArnold of Spartanburg, former\nmember of the commission, and al\nso former member of the house.\nThe senate Wednesday night gave\napproval to a bill which changes the\nname of Winthrop College to\nWinthr op-Johnson college in*\nhonor or Dr. D. B. Johnson, presi\ndent of that institution. Persistent\nefforts were made to defeat this\nmeasure and it was debated sever\nal times, but sentiment in favor of\nplacing Dr. Johnson\u2019s name in con\nnection with that of Mr. Wdnthrop\nwas strong, and the measure has\nbeen sent out over the house for\naction.\nThe senate .Wednesday night also\nexpressed its favor of repealing the\nlaw\u2019 which prohibits the organiza-\ntion of Greek Letter fraternities in*'\nstate educational institutions. The\nbill has been passed and sent to the\nhouse.\nThe so-called \u201cBarber shop\u201d bill,\na bill, passed by the senate, prohibit\ning negro barbers from,v- serving\nwhite women or girls, met its death\nin the house this week. The measure\nwas continued until next year, the\nvote in the house in favor of carry\ning it over being 62 to 40.\nThe bill was introduced by Sena\ntor Claud Martin of Orangeburg.\nUnder the terms of a bill passed\nthis week by the senate and sent\nover to the house, clerks of court\nJ would be required to sell all state\nj revenue stamps, they being allowed\na fee of two per cent for the addir\ntional trouble caused.\nWhen the bill was under discus\ni sion, it was pointed out that in some\nj towns had refused to handle the\nstamps ahd that merchants were in\nconvenienced in being forced to ord\ner from the tax commission.\n\nWhile the senate finance com\nmittee has under consideration the\ngeneral appropriations bill as pass\ned by the house, the house ways and\nmeans committee is considering\nplans for raising the money to meet\nthe appropriations\u2014about $9,9010,\n000.\nAn occupational tax is now being\nconsidered for raising revenue,\ncoupled with a proposal for a tax\non new automobiles of two per cent\npayable at the sale. The proposed\noccupational tax, yet in its embry\nonic stages, is said to provide for a\ntax on hotels, plumbing establish-\n(Continued on page 4)","height":"31552","width":"24440"}}
